Step 2: Tunring the imagies into vector form¶

In [3]:
# assuming data is contained in a train and a validation set
Train_data_dir = Input_1+'train/'

# Set up some parmaeters for data loading
sample_rate = 1.0

# desired dimensions of our images.
img_width, img_height = 168, 128

# different backends (e.g. tensorflow and theano) use different orderings for image data
if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
     input_shape = (3, img_width, img_height)
else:
     input_shape = (img_width, img_height, 3)
        
#for gray scaled data making the channel equal to 1.
if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
    input_shape_grey = (1, img_width, img_height)
else:
    input_shape_grey = (img_width, img_height, 1)
        
Training_class_folders = [i for i in os.listdir(Train_data_dir) if not (i.startswith('.') or i.startswith('Icon'))]
num_classes = len(Training_class_folders)

# Initialise arrays for data storage
X_data = np.ndarray((0, input_shape[0], input_shape[1], input_shape[2]), dtype=np.float)
X_data_grey = np.ndarray((0, input_shape_grey[0], input_shape_grey[1], input_shape_grey[2]), dtype=np.float)
Y_data= np.ndarray(0, dtype=np.str)


for i, file in enumerate(['train']):
    path = Input_1+file
    for i, classes in enumerate(['NORMAL', 'PNEUMONIA']):
        print('Processing images of class {}'.format(classes))
        Class_folder = path + "/" + classes + "/"
        # generate filenames from the data folder and do sampling
        Img_name = [Class_folder+i for i in os.listdir(Class_folder) if not i.startswith('.')] # use this for full dataset
        Img_name = random.sample(Img_name, int(len(Img_name)*sample_rate))
        
        # Create a data array for image data
        count = len(Img_name)
        X_data_part = np.ndarray((count, input_shape[0], input_shape[1], input_shape[2]), dtype=np.float)
        X_data_grey_part = np.ndarray((count, input_shape_grey[0], input_shape_grey[1], input_shape_grey[2]), dtype=np.float)
        # Iterate throuigh the filenames and for each one load the image, resize and normalise
        for i, image_file in enumerate(Img_name):
            # Low the images and resize them
            image = cv2.imread(image_file, cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)
            image = cv2.resize(image, (img_height, img_width), interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC)        
            image = image[:,:,[2,1,0]] # OpenCV and matplotlib use differnet channel oerderings so fix this
            
            image_grey = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
            image_grey = cv2.resize(image_grey, (img_height, img_width), interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC)
            #grayscale has no channel, but convolutions need 4D array thus keeing the channel as 1
            image_grey = np.asarray(image_grey).reshape(image_grey.shape[0],image_grey.shape[1],1)
            #image = image[:,:,0] # OpenCV and matplotlib use differnet channel orderings so fix this
            
            # If channel order of network does not match open cv format swap it
            if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
                image=np.swapaxes(np.swapaxes(image, 1, 2), 0, 1)
            
            # Add image data to data array and normalise
            X_data_part[i] = image
            X_data_part[i] = X_data_part[i]/255
            
            X_data_grey_part[i] = image_grey
            X_data_grey_part[i] = X_data_grey_part[i]/255
            
            # Add label to label array
            Y_data = np.append(Y_data, classes)
            
        if i%100 == 0: print('Processed {} of {} for class {} '.format(i, count, classes))

        print('Processed {} of {} for class {} '.format(i + 1, count, classes))
    
        # Append the part to the overall data array
        X_data = np.append(X_data, X_data_part, axis=0)
        X_data_grey = np.append(X_data_grey, X_data_grey_part, axis=0)
            

print("Data shape: {}".format(X_data.shape))

Processing images of class NORMAL
Processed 153 of 153 for class NORMAL 
Processing images of class PNEUMONIA
Processed 76 of 76 for class PNEUMONIA 
Data shape: (229, 168, 128, 3)

Step 5: Creating the model for CNN model¶

In [13]:
#leNet-5 architecture is refered from = "https://medium.com/@mgazar/lenet-5-in-9-lines-of-code-using-keras-ac99294c8086"

Model2 = keras.Sequential()

Model2.add(Conv2D(filters=6, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape_grey))
Model2.add(AveragePooling2D())

Model2.add(Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu'))
Model2.add(AveragePooling2D())

Model2.add(Flatten())

Model2.add(Dense(units=120, activation='relu'))

Model2.add(Dense(units=84, activation='relu'))

Model2.add(Dense(units=2, activation = 'softmax'))

# Compile the Model1
Model2.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

Model2.summary()

from keras.preprocessing.image import array_to_img

pltsize=4
row_images = 4
col_images = 4

# fit parameters from data
Train_datagen.fit(X_train)

for idx in range(0, 4):
    # Plot the original image
    plt.figure(figsize=(col_images*pltsize, row_images*pltsize))
    plt.subplot(row_images,col_images,1)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.imshow(array_to_img(X_train[idx]),cmap="gray")
    plt.title("Original")
    #plot the randomly seleted augmentation for the original image
    for i in range(row_images * col_images - 1):
        rand_trans = Train_datagen.random_transform(X_train[idx])
        plt.subplot(row_images,col_images,i+2)
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.imshow(array_to_img(rand_trans),cmap="gray")
        plt.title(i)

    plt.show()

In [25]:
VGG16_last_layer = VGG16_model.output

# build a classifier model to put on top of the VGG16 model
A1 = Flatten()(VGG16_last_layer)
A2 = Dense(256, activation='relu')(A1)
A3 = Dropout(0.5)(A2)
final_layer = Dense(num_classes, activation = 'softmax')(A3)

# Assemble the full model out of both parts
FULL_model = keras.Model(VGG16_model.input, final_layer)

# set the first 16 layers (last three conv block before the fully connected layes)
# to non-trainable (weights will not be updated)
for layer in FULL_model.layers[:16]:
    layer.trainable = False

# compile the model with a SGD/momentum optimizer
# and a very slow learning rate.
FULL_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
              optimizer=keras.optimizers.SGD(lr=1e-4, momentum=0.9),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

FULL_model.summary()

Conclusion¶

In conclusion i have provided the table below which compares the prediction of CNN model and CNN model after data augmentation and the third model is the VGG16 model. I have used the smaller dataset, i did try with the larger dataset but it was taking two long to process and i had to shift to the smaller dataset. To check which model performs better i have considered in this case is the F1-measure in all three models to comprare the accuracy.

Below table marks the F1-Measure for the three models
</br>

Model Used F1 score
Logistic Regression 0.90
CNN Model 0.88
CNN Model with data Augmentation 0.67
VGG16 Model 0.87

So as seen in the table we can see that logistic regression has the best accuracy when compared with all the other models. The ineresting thing to notic here is that when we run the CNN model after data augmentation, there is a decrease in the accuracy/F1-measure. This might be due to the attributes used in the data augmentaion where we change the height, zoom it and rescale it. Maybe the attributes i have used might not suit the x-ray dataset or maybe it is beacuse we changed the x-rays where in the first place we need x-ray as a whole. Maybe doing data augmentation on X-rays images doesnt help.

When VGG16 was model was used the F1-measure is as good as CNN model and we can actually used CNN or VGG16 for the dataset provided when comapared to the predictions after the Data augmentation process. Logistic Regression has the highest F1-measure, so that is also an excellent model to use for the given datatset.
